        "answer_count": 1,
        "title": "Hibernate support for JDBC specification 4.3?",
        "body": "<p>In the <a href=\"https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/5.4/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#_system_requirements\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">docs for Hibernate ORM 5.4<\/a> it states that the System Requirements require <em>at least<\/em> Java 1.8 and JDBC 4.2.<\/p>\n<p>The same can be found for <a href=\"https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/6.0/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#_system_requirements\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">the docs for version 6.0<\/a>.<\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hibernate 5.2 and later versions require <em>at least Java 1.8 and JDBC 4.2<\/em>.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>So is the <a href=\"https://jcp.org/aboutJava/communityprocess/mrel/jsr221/index3.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JDBC 4.3 specification<\/a> (<a href=\"https://jcp.org/aboutJava/communityprocess/maintenance/jsr221/JDBC4.3MR-January2017.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">proposed changes<\/a>) supported by Hibernate ORM 5.4? Does it matter? I assume that any unsupported method call will just throw a <code>SQLFeatureNotSupportedException<\/code>.<\/p>\n<p>I just can't find anything that explicitly states that JDBC 4.3 <strong>is<\/strong> or <strong>is not<\/strong> supported and need that cleared up.<\/p>\n",
